"""
MKT Christ Commentary — 1 Samuel chapters 15–16
Run: python3 scripts/zc-christ-1samuel-15-16.py

Ch 15: Saul's disobedience against Amalek; rejection of the disobedient king; obedience > sacrifice.
Ch 16: David anointed in secret; YHWH sees the heart; Spirit departs Saul; David enters service.

Key Christological connections:
- Obedience > sacrifice (15:22) → fulfilled in Christ's complete obedience (Phil 2:8)
- Kingdom transferred to a better neighbor (15:28) → Matt 21:43
- YHWH sees the heart not the face (16:7) → John 7:24 / 2 Cor 5:12
- Shepherd-king called from the flock (16:11-12) → John 10:11
- Spirit-departure as apostasy warning (16:14) → Heb 6:4-6
- David-musician serving the troubled Saul (16:23) → Christ's ministry to the spiritually oppressed
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(type_, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / f'mkt-{type_}' / f'{book}.json'
    return json.loads(p.read_text()) if p.exists() else {}

def save_comm(type_, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / f'mkt-{type_}' / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, text in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = text

CHRIST = {
  "15": {
    "1": "<p>Samuel's commission to Saul — 'YHWH sent me to anoint you king; now listen to the words of YHWH' — establishes that Saul's kingship is entirely derivative from divine appointment. The anointing creates the obligation: the king who was installed by the prophetic word must now obey the prophetic word. Saul's subsequent disobedience is not merely a tactical failure but a theological one — the anointed who rejects the Anointer's command undermines the entire basis of his authority. Christ, the ultimate Anointed, is the one whose obedience is complete precisely because he acknowledges that all authority comes from above (John 19:11).</p>",
    "2": "<p>The YHWH of hosts recalls Amalek's ambush at the Exodus (Exod 17:8-16) and declares the time of reckoning has come. The delayed judgment — YHWH's decision to execute the Amalek sentence through Israel's king — reflects the divine patience and the eventual certainty of covenant-violation consequences. The principle that YHWH's judgment on covenant enemies is delayed but certain prefigures the eschatological judgment Christ will execute (Rev 19:11-15). Amalek's sin was against Israel in its weakness; the judgment comes at Israel's military maturity.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The <em>ḥērem</em> command — 'utterly destroy all they have; do not spare them' — is the holy-war consecration of the enemy to YHWH. The theological logic of <em>ḥērem</em> is that YHWH claims the entire spoil as his own; human retention of any part is theft from YHWH. Christ applies the same logic of total consecration to discipleship: 'Any one of you who does not renounce all that he has cannot be my disciple' (Luke 14:33). The <em>ḥērem</em>'s demand of complete surrender is the OT structural type of total self-surrender to YHWH.</p>",
    "4": "<p>Saul musters the forces at Telaim — 200,000 foot soldiers and 10,000 men of Judah. The separate count for Judah (as in 11:8) foreshadows the north-south division. Saul's command of a unified Israel against a covenant enemy is the high-water mark of his military authority before his disobedience drains it. The marshaling of Israel for YHWH's holy war is the type of the eschatological gathering of the elect for the final battle (Rev 16:14-16).</p>",
    "5": "<p>Saul comes to the city of Amalek and sets an ambush in the wadi. The military preparation is thorough — Saul is an effective commander. His competence in military matters makes his subsequent disobedience more inexplicable and culpable: this is not the mistake of a poorly equipped commander but the deliberate choice of an experienced one. Partial obedience in the accomplished is the more serious failure.</p>",
    "6": "<p>Saul warns the Kenites to leave the Amalekites' territory because the Kenites showed kindness to Israel at the Exodus. The exemption of the Kenites from the <em>ḥērem</em> on the basis of their ancestral covenant kindness illustrates a principle Christ generalizes: 'whoever gives you a cup of water to drink because you belong to Christ will by no means lose his reward' (Mark 9:41). Acts of covenant kindness toward YHWH's people are remembered and rewarded across generations.</p>",
    "7": "<p>Saul attacks the Amalekites from Havilah to Shur, east of Egypt — the full extent of their territory. The comprehensive geography of the campaign indicates a thorough military operation against the designated enemy. The subsequent failure is not incomplete effort but selective retention: he went everywhere but did not complete the consecration.</p>",
    "8": "<p>Saul captures Agag king of the Amalekites alive and completely destroys all the people with the edge of the sword. The sparing of Agag — the king — while executing the people is a fatal inversion of priorities: the representative head of the enemy is preserved while the body is destroyed. The application of <em>ḥērem</em> to the masses but exemption for the king reflects the human tendency to apply divine commands to the anonymous while protecting the powerful. Christ's critique of the Pharisees applies the same pattern: they strain the gnat (small obligations) and swallow the camel (major ones, Matt 23:24).</p>",
    "9": "<p>Saul and the people spare Agag and the best of the sheep and oxen and the fattened calves and the lambs — 'all that was good' — but destroy 'all that was despised and worthless.' The selective retention reveals the operative value system: what YHWH commanded be destroyed is measured against market value, and the economically valuable is retained. This is the logic of the person who obeys God in low-cost areas while retaining what they value most. The Christological counter is Luke 14:26 — love of Christ must exceed the value calculus applied to family, possessions, and self.</p>",
    "10": "<p>The word of YHWH comes to Samuel: 'I regret that I made Saul king, for he has turned from following me and has not obeyed my commands.' The divine regret (<em>niḥamtî</em>) is the anthropopathic expression of YHWH's grief over covenant failure — not a change in the divine nature but a real response to human rejection. Samuel's grief over this word (v11) mirrors YHWH's own — the prophet who anointed Saul shares in the divine sorrow over the anointed's failure. Christ wept over Jerusalem (Luke 19:41) with the same grief over a covenant people's rejection.</p>",
    "11": "<p>Samuel is angry and cries to YHWH all night. The prophetic grief that drives all-night intercession is Samuel's participation in YHWH's own sorrow. The night of prayer before a decisive confrontation echoes Christ's Gethsemane vigil — the night of prayer preceding the confrontation with covenant failure and its judgment. Samuel will execute YHWH's judgment on Agag in the morning (v32-33); Christ will bear YHWH's judgment on human covenant failure at the cross.</p>",
    "12": "<p>Samuel rises early to meet Saul, and is told Saul went to Carmel and set up a monument for himself, then turned and passed on to Gilgal. The monument (<em>yāḏ</em>) Saul erects for himself is a self-memorial — a self-glorifying act that contrasts with the YHWH-memorial stones (7:12; Josh 4:7) placed by faithful leaders. The king who should have been consecrating YHWH's spoil is instead consecrating his own reputation. Christ condemns the self-promoting piety that 'stands on street corners to be seen by others' (Matt 6:5) — Saul's monument is its OT equivalent.</p>",
    "13": "<p>Saul greets Samuel: 'I have carried out the word of YHWH.' The claim of complete obedience immediately before a confrontation about incomplete obedience is the anatomy of self-deception. Saul has convinced himself that partial obedience counts as full obedience — a failure of self-knowledge that Christ addresses in the Sermon on the Mount: 'Not everyone who says to me, Lord, Lord, will enter the kingdom of heaven' (Matt 7:21). The profession of complete obedience and the reality of selective obedience can coexist in the same person.</p>",
    "14": "<p>Samuel's devastating counter: 'What then is this bleating of sheep in my ears and the lowing of cattle that I hear?' The animals whose destruction YHWH commanded are audibly present at the moment Saul claims complete obedience. The evidence contradicts the claim without need for lengthy argument. Christ's similar technique — 'you say you love the Father, but these are your works' — uses observable reality to pierce self-justifying profession (John 8:41-44).</p>",
    "15": "<p>Saul deflects: 'They have brought them from the Amalekites, for the people spared the best of the sheep and cattle to sacrifice to YHWH your God.' Three deflections in one sentence: (1) it was the people, not me; (2) it was for sacrifice — a religious justification; (3) 'your God' rather than 'our God' — unconscious distancing. The religious justification for covenant violation is a recurring pattern: the sacrifice excuse converts disobedience into apparent piety. Christ addresses this in Matt 15:5-6: Corban — religious vow — used to circumvent the command to honor parents.</p>",
    "16": "<p>Samuel says: 'Stop! Let me tell you what YHWH said to me last night.' The prophetic word cuts off the self-justifying speech. The authority of the divine word over human self-explanation is the hermeneutical principle of all prophetic confrontation: YHWH's assessment takes precedence over the self-assessment of the one being confronted. Christ exercises the same authority: 'But I say to you' overrides the traditional self-justifications of Torah interpretation (Matt 5:22,28,34).</p>",
    "17": "<p>Samuel invokes Saul's early humility: 'Though you were small in your own eyes, were you not head of the tribes of Israel?' The connection between being 'small in one's own eyes' (<em>qāṭōn bəʿênêḵā</em>) and being appointed to YHWH's service is the OT principle that Christ makes explicit: 'whoever humbles himself will be exalted, and whoever exalts himself will be humbled' (Matt 23:12). Saul's initial humility was the character that qualified him; its loss — expressed in the self-monument at Carmel (v12) — is the character change that disqualified him.</p>",
    "18": "<p>YHWH sent Saul on a mission: 'Go and devote to destruction the sinners, the Amalekites; fight against them until they are consumed.' The mission statement was precise — total devotion to destruction. The gap between the specific command and the actual execution defines Saul's failure. Obedience to YHWH's commands is not measured by effort or proximity but by correspondence between the instruction and the action. Christ's disciples are called to obey 'everything I have commanded you' (Matt 28:20) — not a selection.</p>",
    "19": "<p>'Why did you not obey the voice of YHWH? You pounced on the spoil and did what was evil in the sight of YHWH.' The verb <em>ʿîṭ</em> (pounce/fly upon) is used for predatory speed — Saul moved swiftly on the spoil he wanted to keep. The contrast between the speed with which Israel attacked the spoil and the incompleteness with which they executed the <em>ḥērem</em> shows the operative priority: the economically desirable was pursued eagerly; the theologically required was performed partially. Zeal in the direction of self-interest is not the same as obedience.</p>",
    "20": "<p>Saul continues the defense: 'I have obeyed the voice of YHWH; I went on the mission YHWH sent me on, I brought Agag king of Amalek, and I devoted the Amalekites to destruction.' His claim of obedience has now been stated twice (v13, v20) — each time slightly updated as the confrontation narrows. The exception he is retaining — Agag, plus the animals — he mentions as evidence of success rather than failure. Self-justification often focuses on what was done rather than what was not done.</p>",
    "21": "<p>'But the people took of the spoil, sheep and oxen, the best of the things devoted to destruction, to sacrifice to YHWH your God at Gilgal.' The sacrifice-at-Gilgal rationale is the religious appropriation of disobedience. Gilgal was a legitimate sacred site; sacrifice was a legitimate act of worship. The combination of legitimate site + legitimate act applied to illegitimately retained spoil is the anatomy of religious cover for self-serving choices. The form of worship is maintained; the substance is corrupted.</p>",
    "22": "<p>'Has YHWH as great delight in burnt offerings and sacrifices as in obeying the voice of YHWH? Behold, to obey is better than sacrifice, and to listen than the fat of rams.' Samuel's prophetic principle — <em>šāmaʿ mizzébaḥ ṭôḇ</em> (obedience is better than sacrifice) — is the OT's most concentrated statement of the priestly-prophetic tension. The prophets from Amos to Hosea to Isaiah develop this theme: ritual acts do not substitute for covenant faithfulness. Christ quotes Hosea 6:6 ('I desire mercy, not sacrifice') twice in Matthew (9:13; 12:7), applying it precisely to those who use religious forms to avoid covenant obligations. The fulfillment is Christ’s own obedience — ‘not to offer sacrifice, but in the prepared body: \"Behold, I have come to do your will\"’ (Heb 10:5-7).</p>",
    "23": "<p>'For rebellion is as the sin of divination (<em>qesem</em>), and stubbornness is as iniquity and idolatry (<em>tərāpîm</em>). Because you have rejected the word of YHWH, he has also rejected you from being king.' The equation of rebellion with divination and stubbornness with idolatry is a radical theological claim: willful disobedience to YHWH's word is structurally equivalent to seeking guidance from forbidden sources and worshipping substitute objects. The person who substitutes their own judgment for YHWH's word has made themselves an oracle and their own preferences an idol. Christ makes the same equation: 'Why do you call me Lord, Lord, and not do what I say?' (Luke 6:46) — nominal lordship that does not produce obedience is idolatry of self.</p>",
    "24": "<p>Saul confesses: 'I have sinned, for I have transgressed the commandment of YHWH and your words, because I feared the people and listened to their voice.' The confession is real but its motive is fear of consequences rather than contrition over the nature of the sin. Saul confesses what he did (transgressed the commandment) and gives its cause (fear of the people) but does not confess the theological category: he chose the approval of people over obedience to YHWH. This is the precise failure Jesus identifies in the Pharisees: 'they loved the glory that comes from man more than the glory that comes from God' (John 12:43).</p>",
    "25": "<p>Saul asks Samuel to forgive his sin and return with him to worship YHWH. The request for return-to-worship rather than genuine repentance reveals the priority: Saul wants the external covenant acts restored (Samuel's company, the public worship) rather than the internal covenant relationship renewed. The performance of worship as cover for unrepentance is what Christ condemns: 'first be reconciled to your brother, and then come and offer your gift' (Matt 5:24). The order matters: relationship before ritual.</p>",
    "26": "<p>Samuel refuses to return with Saul: 'I will not return with you. For you have rejected the word of YHWH, and YHWH has rejected you from being king over Israel.' The double rejection — Saul's rejection of YHWH's word answered by YHWH's rejection of Saul's kingship — is the covenant principle of reciprocal response. Christ articulates the same principle: 'whoever denies me before men, I also will deny before my Father' (Matt 10:33). The rejection of YHWH's word is not a neutral act; it returns to the one who rejects it.</p>",
    "27": "<p>As Samuel turns to go, Saul seizes the hem of his robe and it tears. The tearing of Samuel's robe becomes the prophetic sign of the kingdom's tearing from Saul. The <em>kānāp</em> (corner/hem) that Saul grabs — the same term used for the garment corner David will cut from Saul's robe in 24:4-5 — is the symbol of identity and authority. The torn robe enacts the judicial sentence before Samuel announces it. Physical objects in the prophetic tradition repeatedly act out what is simultaneously being spoken (cf. Jeremiah's broken flask, Ezek's shaved hair).</p>",
    "28": "<p>'YHWH has torn the kingdom of Israel from you today and has given it to a neighbor of yours, who is better than you.' The transfer of the kingdom to 'a better neighbor' is the formal announcement of the Davidic succession. Christ applies the same transfer principle to Israel in Matthew 21:43: 'The kingdom of God will be taken away from you and given to a people producing its fruits.' The kingdom belongs to YHWH; it is given to stewards who will bear fruit for him; when they fail, it is transferred. Saul-to-David is the historical type; Israel-to-church is the eschatological fulfillment.</p>",
    "29": "<p>'The Glory of Israel (<em>neṣaḥ yiśrāʾēl</em>) will not lie or change his mind; for he is not a man, that he should change his mind.' YHWH's immutability — specifically, his unswerving commitment once he has declared a judgment or a promise — is the theological ground of prophetic confidence. This is in tension with the 'regret' (<em>niḥam</em>) of vv11 and 35, which the text itself acknowledges (v29b: 'for he is not a man that he should repent'). The 'regret' is anthropopathic (YHWH's real emotional response to human failure); the 'not changing mind' is ontological (YHWH's judicial decisions stand). Hebrews 13:8 applies the same immutability to Christ: 'Jesus Christ is the same yesterday and today and forever.'</p>",
    "30": "<p>Saul's plea shifts: 'I have sinned; yet honor me now before the elders of my people and before Israel, and return with me.' The confession of sin now instrumentalized for social purpose — 'I've confessed, so now restore my honor' — reveals that the confession was not the goal but the means to restore public standing. The distinction between genuine repentance (which leads to transformation) and performative repentance (which leads to reputation management) is made explicit here. Christ identifies the same pattern: 'they love to stand and pray in the synagogues and at the street corners, that they may be seen by others' (Matt 6:5).</p>",
    "31": "<p>Samuel returns and follows Saul back. Saul worships YHWH. The external compliance achieved by pressure — Samuel accompanying Saul for the sake of public appearance — is the kind of religious cover that produces the form of covenant practice without its substance. Samuel complies; YHWH has already declared the kingdom forfeited. The public worship act does not change the judicial sentence of v26-28.</p>",
    "32": "<p>Samuel says: 'Bring Agag king of the Amalekites here to me.' Agag comes to Samuel 'cheerfully (<em>maʿădannōṯ</em>)' — either expecting mercy or fatally misreading the situation. His words: 'Surely the bitterness of death has passed.' The condemned man's belief that judgment has been averted is the most poignant note of his appearance. The delay of judgment does not mean its cancellation — a principle Christ articulates in the parable of the persistent widow: YHWH 'will give justice to his elect who cry to him day and night' (Luke 18:7-8). Agag's cheerful arrival precedes his execution by one sentence.</p>",
    "33": "<p>Samuel says: 'As your sword has made women childless, so shall your mother be childless among women.' He hacks Agag to pieces before YHWH at Gilgal. The principle of proportional judgment — the violence Agag inflicted on others' mothers is returned to his own — is the lex talionis applied at the prophetic level. The execution 'before YHWH' at Gilgal (the covenant-renewal site) frames it as a covenant-judicial act, not mere military violence. Christ is the one before whom all judgment is finally executed: 'the Father judges no one, but has given all judgment to the Son' (John 5:22).</p>",
    "34": "<p>Samuel goes to Ramah and Saul goes to his house at Gibeah of Saul. The two figures depart in opposite directions — the prophet and the rejected king — and will not see each other again (v35). The separation of prophet and king is the enacted form of the divine rejection: the word of YHWH no longer comes to Saul through Samuel. The prophetic silence that follows Saul through the rest of his reign is the lived experience of the rejection pronounced here.</p>",
    "35": "<p>Samuel did not see Saul again until the day of Samuel's death — yet Samuel grieved for Saul, and YHWH regretted that he had made Saul king over Israel. The closing verse holds together divine regret and divine immutability (cf. v29): the regret is real, the judgment is irrevocable, and Samuel's grief participates in YHWH's own. The grief that does not change the judicial outcome — the combination of genuine sorrow and firm decision — is the pattern of divine justice: 'God did not spare the angels when they sinned' (2 Pet 2:4) yet 'he does not willingly afflict or grieve the children of men' (Lam 3:33). The tension belongs to the character of YHWH as both just and compassionate.</p>"
  },
  "16": {
    "1": "<p>YHWH asks Samuel: 'How long will you mourn for Saul, since I have rejected him from being king over Israel? Fill your horn with oil and go. I will send you to Jesse the Bethlehemite, for I have provided for myself a king among his sons.' The divine redirect from mourning to mission is the pattern of prophetic recommissioning after loss. Prolonged mourning for what YHWH has ended becomes an obstacle to what YHWH is beginning. Christ applies the same principle: 'Let the dead bury their own dead; but as for you, go and proclaim the kingdom of God' (Luke 9:60). The capacity to release what YHWH has ended is the prerequisite for receiving what YHWH is beginning.</p>",
    "2": "<p>Samuel fears Saul and objects: 'If Saul hears, he will kill me.' The prophet who just executed Agag before YHWH is afraid to anoint a new king because of Saul's surveillance. YHWH provides a cover story: take a heifer for sacrifice, invite Jesse, and in that context perform the anointing. The practical wisdom of the cover — a legitimate cultic act that creates a plausible reason for Samuel's presence at Bethlehem — is not deception but prudential protection of a divine mission. Christ similarly moved through hostile territory on God's timing: 'his hour had not yet come' (John 7:30).</p>",
    "3": "<p>YHWH will show Samuel what to do at Bethlehem; he will show him the one to anoint. The step-by-step divine guidance — go first, I will instruct you further once you arrive — is the model of prophetic commission: YHWH gives enough guidance for the next step without necessarily disclosing the whole mission in advance. Abraham received the same kind of guidance ('go to the land I will show you'); the apostles in Acts receive it step by step. Faith acts on revealed next-steps rather than waiting for complete disclosure.</p>",
    "4": "<p>Samuel does as YHWH commanded and comes to Bethlehem. The elders of the city tremble at his coming and ask: 'Do you come peaceably?' A traveling prophet of Samuel's authority and recent history (the Saul confrontation) arriving without warning was both an honor and a potential threat. The elders' question is reasonable: prophetic visits in the narrative tradition often preceded divine judgment on a community.</p>",
    "5": "<p>Samuel assures them he comes peaceably and consecrates Jesse and his sons for the sacrificial meal. The consecration (<em>wayyəqaddēš</em>) of the family before the meal ensures proper ritual preparation. The sacred meal that will provide cover for the anointing is itself conducted with full cultic integrity — the cover story is a real event, not merely a pretense. The anointing will happen within a genuinely holy context.</p>",
    "6": "<p>When Eliab enters, Samuel thinks: 'Surely YHWH's anointed is before him.' Eliab is tall, firstborn, and impressive — exactly the kind of man Israel chose when they asked for a king 'like all the nations.' Samuel's immediate assumption that the impressive eldest son is YHWH's choice shows that even the prophet who anointed Saul on the basis of his impressive appearance has not yet fully internalized the corrective lesson. The same evaluative framework that produced Saul is Samuel's initial response to Eliab.</p>",
    "7": "<p>'Do not look on his appearance or on the height of his stature, because I have rejected him. For YHWH sees not as man sees; man looks on the outward appearance, but YHWH looks on the heart (<em>lēḇāḇ</em>).' The most famous statement of divine evaluation in Samuel is simultaneously a correction of Samuel's seeing and a theological principle for all human evaluation of YHWH's choices. Christ applies the same principle against surface-level religious evaluation: 'Do not judge by appearances, but judge with right judgment' (John 7:24). Paul's application — 'we no longer know Christ according to the flesh' (2 Cor 5:16) — means YHWH's way of seeing has become the standard for covenant community evaluation.</p>",
    "8": "<p>Jesse calls Abinadab and passes him before Samuel; YHWH has not chosen him. The rejection of son after son — without external explanation — requires Samuel to wait through YHWH's sovereign process. The repeated 'YHWH has not chosen this one' is the prophetic experience of divine selection that exceeds human evaluation categories. YHWH's negative is not arbitrary; the positive will be explained only in retrospect, in David's subsequent career.</p>",
    "9": "<p>Shammah passes before Samuel; YHWH has not chosen him. The third rejection completes the triple-rejection pattern (cf. vv6-9) that establishes the principle definitively: the obvious candidates are not YHWH's choice. The pattern of YHWH bypassing the expected and choosing the unexpected is the structural template for the incarnation: 'Can anything good come out of Nazareth?' (John 1:46).</p>",
    "10": "<p>Jesse makes seven of his sons pass before Samuel, and Samuel says: 'YHWH has not chosen any of these.' The exhaustion of the obvious candidates — all seven present sons rejected — forces the disclosure of the absent one. The process of elimination that makes the hidden son visible is the narrative technique that heightens the unexpected nature of YHWH's choice. Seven sons present, none chosen; the eighth, absent, is the one.</p>",
    "11": "<p>Samuel asks: 'Are all your sons here?' Jesse acknowledges the youngest, who is tending the sheep. 'Send and get him, for we will not sit down until he comes here.' The youngest tending sheep is the classic insignificance-position in ancient family structures: the shepherd-son is at the bottom of the inheritance order and on the periphery of the family's social world. YHWH's anointed is found at the sheep. The pattern — shepherd called to be king — is explicitly applied to Christ in John 10:11 and fulfilled in the Good Shepherd who is also the messianic King.</p>",
    "12": "<p>The young man is brought in: ruddy (<em>ʾaḏmônî</em>), with beautiful eyes and handsome appearance. YHWH says: 'Arise, anoint him, for this is he.' David's appearance is not irrelevant — it is simply not the basis for YHWH's choice. The difference from Saul: Saul's appearance was the primary thing noted and the thing Israel emphasized; David's appearance is noted after YHWH has already declared his choice. YHWH chooses by heart; he does not choose the ugly. The incarnate Christ likewise had 'no beauty that we should desire him' (Isa 53:2) in suffering — the kingly beauty appeared in resurrection (Rev 1:13-16).</p>",
    "14": "<p>The Spirit of YHWH departs from Saul and a harmful spirit from YHWH terrifies him. The judicial withdrawal of the Spirit — replacing the divine empowerment with a divine affliction — is the covenant consequence of persistent disobedience. The 'evil spirit from YHWH' (<em>rûaḥ rāʿāh mēʾiṯ YHWH</em>) is not demonic possession in the later technical sense but YHWH's judicial abandonment leaving Saul vulnerable to psychological deterioration. Hebrews 6:4-6 warns that those who have 'tasted the heavenly gift' and then 'fallen away' make restoration impossible — Saul's condition is the OT prototype of this apostasy warning. The Spirit that came on him in 10:6-10 and made him 'another man' is now withdrawn.</p>",
    "15": "<p>Saul's servants observe his condition and tell him a harmful spirit from God is troubling him. The servants' diagnosis is accurate — they correctly identify the spirit's divine origin rather than attributing it to natural causes. Their therapeutic proposal (music to soothe the spirit) reflects the ANE understanding of music as spiritually efficacious — not merely emotionally calming but capable of addressing spiritual disturbance. The remedy they propose will introduce the one who will succeed Saul into his very household.</p>",
    "16": "<p>The servants recommend finding a man skilled at playing the lyre. When the harmful spirit from God is upon Saul, the musician will play and Saul will be well. The servant's proposal is practical and YHWH's providence is operating through it: the most natural human solution to a spiritual problem will be the instrument for installing YHWH's anointed in the house of the rejected king. Providence typically operates through the natural and ordinary.</p>",
    "17": "<p>Saul instructs his servants to find him a man who plays well and bring him. The king who has been rejected and is now troubled by an evil spirit is actively seeking the one who will displace him — unaware of David's identity or anointing. The irony is deep: Saul seeks relief from his affliction; YHWH sends the one whose arrival will make Saul's condition permanent. Saul's request creates the opening that installs his successor in his own house.</p>",
    "18": "<p>A servant knows of David son of Jesse: 'a man skillful in playing, a man of valor, a warrior, prudent in speech, a man of good presence, and YHWH is with him.' The servant's enumeration of David's qualities — musical skill, valor, eloquence, presence, divine favor — is the most comprehensive character summary in the David narrative to this point. The final quality — 'YHWH is with him' (<em>YHWH ʿimmô</em>) — is the defining one. It is the same quality that will characterize David throughout his career and that Mary's angel announces for Jesus: 'YHWH is with you' (Luke 1:28).</p>",
    "19": "<p>Saul sends to Jesse asking for David. The royal command to Jesse — 'send me David your son, who is with the sheep' — is the official summons that moves David from the shepherd field to the royal court. The transition from shepherd to royal service will be completed when he enters Saul's house (v21). The path from Bethlehem's sheep to Jerusalem's throne runs through the house of the man who will eventually seek his life.</p>",
    "20": "<p>Jesse sends David to Saul with a donkey, bread, a skin of wine, and a young goat — a gift appropriate for a royal introduction. The provisions are the household gift of a Judahite farmer sending his son to court service: not extravagant but adequate. The contrast between the donkeys Kish sent with Saul (9:3) to find what was lost and the donkey Jesse sends with David is the narrative's quiet bookend: one journey ended with a king-in-waiting meeting his anointer; this journey begins a king-in-waiting's service to the rejected king.</p>",
    "21": "<p>David comes to Saul and enters his service; Saul loves him greatly and David becomes his armor-bearer. The anointed future king serves as the personal attendant of the rejected current king — the kenotic structure of David's position in Saul's court is the OT type of what Paul describes in Philippians 2:7: Christ 'took the form of a servant' and 'humbled himself.' The greatest will serve among them as the least (Luke 22:26-27). David's armor-bearer role will produce the military opportunity for Goliath (ch17) without removing the humility of the service.</p>",
    "22": "<p>Saul sends to Jesse asking David to remain permanently in his service, 'for he has found favor in my sight.' The favor David finds in Saul's eyes (<em>māṣāʾ ḥēn bəʿênāyw</em>) is YHWH's hand at work — the same formula applied to Joseph in Potiphar's house (Gen 39:4), to Moses before Pharaoh (Exod 3:21), and ultimately fulfilled in Christ who 'increased in favor with God and man' (Luke 2:52). Those anointed by YHWH find favor precisely where they serve, even when serving those who will eventually oppose them.</p>",
    "23": "<p>Whenever the evil spirit from God is upon Saul, David takes the lyre and plays with his hand, and Saul is refreshed and well, and the evil spirit departs from him. The musician whose playing drives away the spirit that afflicts the rejected king is the pastoral type of Christ's ministry to the spiritually oppressed — the ministry Isaiah describes as 'binding up the brokenhearted' and 'proclaiming liberty to the captives' (Isa 61:1, cited by Jesus in Luke 4:18). David's music is the prototype of the ministry of the Anointed who brings relief to those afflicted by spiritual oppression. The Spirit that departed from Saul when David was anointed (v14) departs from Saul again when David plays.</p>"
  }
}

